        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This is secondary science. For gas at 30 K, an optically thick thermalised 13CO 6-5 line would be very well detected. The OT gives an rms allowing detection of lines ~1K (0.4 K rms / channel). Gas spread in velocity over 0 to 50 km/s (w.r.t estimated pulsar space motion) would occupy 3 spectral channels. This somewhat pessimistic case (i.e. no faster flows such as infall) can just resolve expected signatures. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Resolution elements of 0.2 arcsec correspond to 50 AU at the source distance of 250 pc. The expected disc size is 0.2-1 arcsec. The disc is unlikely to exceed ~1.5 arcsec, based on optical imaging discussed in the science case, Figure 3. Our setup gives a largest angular scale of 1.9 arcsec. We have complementary single-dish data with an 8 arcsec beam, sampled by jiggling at 2 arcsec spacings, across a 2 arcmin field. Hence we will have combined spatial sampling from 0.2 arcsec to 2 arcmin. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The sensitivity is based on the continuum flux. As described in the science case, we predict 1.6 mJy per resolution element on average, for the _largest_ expected disc (covering 20 pixels in area), up to 32 mJy if the disc is unresolved. An rms of 0.4 mJy thus gives 4-sigma/pixel in the worst case. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Band 9 is required for compability with the exisiting detection (Figure 1). We do not have a robust detection in Band 7 and no other bands are in hand for single dish observations. With ALMA, other bands (in recommended weather octiles) would take _longer_ times, because of the unusually steep spectral index (~4) for this dust source. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_NON_STD_CONT_FREQ</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
