    <prp:abstract>Planets and asteroids can survive post-main-sequence stellar evolution, as around some white dwarfs - however, a massive star that becomes a supernova should destroy any planetary system. It has been proposed that a second generation of planets can form from a circum-neutron star material, but no analogues to cool proto-planetary discs around young stars have been discovered. We have recently detected the nearby mid-aged Geminga pulsar in submillimetre emission characteristic of dust particles, and have further time to look at gas velocities. We hypothesise that ~3 M(Earth) of dust has been recently swept up from the interstellar medium around Geminga, and could be in a compact disc suitable to re-form planets. We propose for ALMA time to image the source geometry and test the disc formation hypothesis.
</prp:abstract>
